## Chat Template Implementation in llama.cpp - Complete Analysis

I've thoroughly analyzed the llama.cpp chat template system. Here's a comprehensive breakdown of how templates are implemented, registered, and used:

### 1. Core Data Structures

**Main Chat Template Type** (`common/chat.h`):
```cpp
struct common_chat_template {
    jinja::program prog;           // Compiled Jinja template program
    std::string bos_tok;           // BOS token
    std::string eos_tok;           // EOS token
    std::string src;               // Original template source
    chat_template_caps caps;       // Capabilities detected from template
};
```

**Chat Templates Container** (`common/chat.cpp`, line 223):
```cpp
struct common_chat_templates {
    bool add_bos;
    bool add_eos;
    bool has_explicit_template;
    std::unique_ptr<common_chat_template> template_default;  // Always set (defaults to chatml)
    std::unique_ptr<common_chat_template> template_tool_use; // Optional variant
};
```

**Common Chat Parameters** (`common/chat.h`):
```cpp
struct common_chat_params {
    common_chat_format format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;
    std::string prompt;
    std::string grammar;
    bool grammar_lazy = false;
    std::string generation_prompt;
    bool supports_thinking = false;
    std::string thinking_start_tag;  // e.g., "<think>"
    std::string thinking_end_tag;    // e.g., "</think>"
    std::vector<common_grammar_trigger> grammar_triggers;
    std::vector<std::string> preserved_tokens;
    std::vector<std::string> additional_stops;
    std::string parser;
};
```

### 2. Template Registration & Auto-Detection

**Initialization Function** (`common/chat.cpp`, lines 591-689):
The main entry point is `common_chat_templates_init()`, which:

1. **Checks for explicit override** - From `--chat-template` argument
2. **Falls back to model metadata** - Calls `llama_model_chat_template(model, nullptr)` to get default template from model
3. **Loads tool_use variant** - Calls `llama_model_chat_template(model, "tool_use")` if available
4. **Uses ChatML as fallback** - Default: `CHATML_TEMPLATE_SRC` (defined at line 562)

The template source is then compiled into a Jinja program:
```cpp
jinja::lexer lexer;
auto lexer_res = lexer.tokenize(src);
this->prog = jinja::parse_from_tokens(lexer_res);
this->caps = jinja::caps_get(prog);
```

### 3. Built-in Default Template

**ChatML Template** (`common/chat.cpp`, lines 562-568):
```cpp
#define CHATML_TEMPLATE_SRC \
    "{%- for message in messages -%}\n" \
    "  {{- '<|im_start|>' + message.role + '\n' + message.content + '<|im_end|>\n' -}}\n" \
    "{%- endfor -%}\n" \
    "{%- if add_generation_prompt -%}\n" \
    "  {{- '<|im_start|>assistant\n' -}}\n" \
    "{%- endif -%}"
```

### 4. Specialized Template Handlers (Pattern)

**Location**: `common/chat.cpp`, lines 1634-1691 (`common_chat_try_specialized_template()`)

The system implements specialized handlers for templates that don't fit the generic auto-parser pattern. These are invoked based on **marker detection**:

#### Implemented Specialized Handlers:

1. **Ministral/Magistral Large 3** (lines 825-940)
   - Detection: `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` + `[TOOL_CALLS]` + `[ARGS]` but NO `[CALL_ID]`
   - Features: Special reasoning structure fixes, thinking tags `[THINK]...[/THINK]`

2. **GPT-OSS** (lines 942-1080)
   - Detection: `<|channel|>` marker present
   - Features: Channel-based structure, unique tool response format

3. **Functionary v3.2** (lines 1081-1174)
   - Detection: `>>>all` for content + `>>>${recipient}` for tool calls
   - Features: Recipient-based format

4. **Kimi K2 Thinking** (lines 1175-1290)
   - Detection: `<|tool_calls_section_begin|>` + `<|tool_call_begin|>`
   - Features: Unique tool ID format `functions.<name>:<index>`

5. **LFM2** (lines 1298-1369)
   - Detection: `<|tool_list_start|>...<|tool_list_end|>`
   - Features: Python-style tool calls

6. **LFM2.5** (lines 1377-1444)
   - Detection: `List of tools: [` (no special tokens)
   - Features: Simplified tool list format

7. **GigaChatV3** (lines 1446-1633)
   - Detection: `<|role_sep|>` + `<|message_sep|>` but NO `<|function_call|>`

#### Handler Signature Pattern:

Every handler follows this signature:
```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_<template_name>(
    const common_chat_template & tmpl,
    const autoparser::generation_params & inputs);
```

#### Handler Structure (Generic Pattern):

```cpp
common_chat_params data;

// 1. Apply template to render the prompt
data.prompt = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;

// 2. Declare thinking/reasoning support
data.supports_thinking = true;
data.thinking_start_tag = "<think>";
data.thinking_end_tag = "</think>";

// 3. List all token markers used
data.preserved_tokens = {
    "<think>", "</think>", 
    "<|tool_calls|>", // etc
};

// 4. Build PEG parser using builder
auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
    auto generation_prompt = p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt, "<think>");
    auto reasoning = extract_reasoning 
        ? p.optional("<think>" + p.reasoning(p.until("</think>")) + "</think>") 
        : p.eps();

    if (has_tools && inputs.tool_choice != COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE) {
        // Build tool parsing logic
        auto tool_choice = p.choice();
        foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
            auto & func = tool.at("function");
            auto name = func.at("name");
            auto & schema = func.at("parameters");

            tool_choice |= p.rule("tool-" + name, 
                p.tool_open(...) + p.tool_args(p.schema(...)) + p.tool_close(...));
        });
        return generation_prompt + reasoning + content + tool_calls;
    }

    // Content-only fallback
    return generation_prompt + reasoning + p.content(p.rest());
});

data.parser = parser.save();

// 5. Build grammar for tool calls (optional)
if (include_grammar) {
    data.grammar_lazy = true;  // Defer grammar gen until needed
    data.grammar = build_grammar([&](const common_grammar_builder & builder) {
        foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
            auto schema = tool.at("function").at("parameters");
            builder.resolve_refs(schema);
        });
        parser.build_grammar(builder, data.grammar_lazy);
    });

    data.grammar_triggers = {
        { COMMON_GRAMMAR_TRIGGER_TYPE_WORD, "<|tool_call_begin|>" }
    };
}

return data;
```

### 5. Auto-Parser Fallback (Generic Handler)

**Location**: `common/chat.cpp`, lines 1781-1804

When no specialized handler matches, the system uses differential auto-parsing:

```cpp
if (auto result = common_chat_try_specialized_template(tmpl, src, params)) {
    result->generation_prompt = params.generation_prompt;
    return *result;
}

// Fallback to auto-parser
try {
    struct autoparser::autoparser autoparser;
    autoparser.analyze_template(tmpl);
    auto auto_params = autoparser::peg_generator::generate_parser(tmpl, params, autoparser);
    auto_params.supports_thinking = autoparser.reasoning.mode != autoparser::reasoning_mode::NONE;
    // ... set thinking tags, etc
    return auto_params;
} catch (const std::exception & e) {
    throw std::invalid_argument(std::string("Unable to generate parser for this template. Automatic parser generation failed: ") + e.what());
}
```

The **autoparser** (`common/chat-auto-parser.h`, `common/chat-auto-parser.cpp`) performs differential analysis:
- Compares template output with `add_generation_prompt=false` vs `true`
- Analyzes reasoning markers (`<think>`, `[THINK]`, etc.)
- Detects content wrapping patterns
- Identifies tool call formats (JSON native, tag-based, etc.)
- Extracts marker positions and builds a custom PEG parser

### 6. Template Application Flow

**Main Entry**: `common_chat_templates_apply()` (`common/chat.h`, lines 229-230)

**For Jinja-enabled mode** (lines 1693-1804):
1. Convert input messages to JSON using template capabilities
2. Apply **message workarounds** for template compatibility:
   - `map_developer_role_to_system()` - Convert developer role (except GPT-OSS)
   - `system_message_not_supported()` - Merge system messages if not supported
   - `requires_non_null_content()` - Add empty content string to tool calls
   - `convert_tool_responses_gemma4()` - Convert tool messages for Gemma4
   - `func_args_not_string()` - Convert argument formats

3. **Render template twice** to determine generation prompt:
   - With `add_generation_prompt=false`
   - With `add_generation_prompt=true`
   - Calculate diff to find the generation prompt portion

4. **Try specialized handler** via `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`
5. **Fallback to auto-parser** if no specialized handler matched

### 7. Key API Functions

**File**: `common/chat.h`

```cpp
// Initialize templates from model or override
common_chat_templates_ptr common_chat_templates_init(
    const struct llama_model * model,
    const std::string & chat_template_override,
    const std::string & bos_token_override = "",
    const std::string & eos_token_override = "");

// Apply templates with inputs
struct common_chat_params common_chat_templates_apply(
    const struct common_chat_templates * tmpls,
    const struct common_chat_templates_inputs & inputs);

// Get template source
std::string common_chat_templates_source(
    const struct common_chat_templates * tmpls, 
    const std::string & variant = "");

// Parse output using generated PEG parser
common_chat_msg common_chat_peg_parse(
    const common_peg_arena & src_parser,
    const std::string & input,
    bool is_partial,
    const common_chat_parser_params & params);
```

### 8. Adding a New Specialized Template Handler

To add support for a new template format, follow this pattern:

**Step 1: Create detection logic** in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`:
```cpp
if (src.find("<unique_marker>") != std::string::npos && 
    src.find("<another_marker>") != std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: MyTemplate\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_my_template(tmpl, params);
}
```

**Step 2: Implement the handler**:
```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_my_template(
    const common_chat_template & tmpl,
    const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    // Set basic info
    data.prompt = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = true;
    data.thinking_start_tag = "<think>";
    data.thinking_end_tag = "</think>";
    data.preserved_tokens = { "<think>", "</think>", /* ... */ };

    // Build the PEG parser
    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        // Define your parser using builder DSL
        // Use p.tool(), p.content(), p.reasoning(), etc.
        return your_parser_expression;
    });
    data.parser = parser.save();

    // Build grammar if needed
    if (has_tools && inputs.tool_choice != COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE) {
        data.grammar = build_grammar([&](const common_grammar_builder & builder) {
            // ... build schema constraints
        });
        data.grammar_triggers = { ... };
    }

    return data;
}
```

### 9. Helper Classes & Functions

**PEG Builder** (`common/chat-peg-parser.h`):
- `common_chat_peg_builder` - DSL for building parsers
- Methods: `p.tool()`, `p.tool_name()`, `p.tool_args()`, `p.content()`, `p.reasoning()`, `p.prefix()`, `p.until()`, `p.repeat()`, etc.
- `build_chat_peg_parser()` - Template function to build parsers

**Auto-Parser Components** (`common/chat-auto-parser.h`):
- `analyze_reasoning` - Detects reasoning format
- `analyze_content` - Detects content wrapping
- `analyze_tools` - Detects tool call format
- `autoparser` - Orchestrates differential analysis
- `peg_generator` - Generates PEG parser from analysis

### 10. Files Reference

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `common/chat.h` | Main interface definitions |
| `common/chat.cpp` | Implementation (1963 lines) - contains all handlers |
| `common/chat-auto-parser.h` | Auto-parser interface (438 lines) |
| `common/chat-peg-parser.h` | PEG builder interface (194 lines) |
| `common/chat-auto-parser-helpers.h` | Helper utilities |
| `common/chat-auto-parser-helpers.cpp` | Helper implementations |
| `common/chat-auto-parser.cpp` | Auto-parser implementation |
| `common/chat-peg-parser.cpp` | PEG builder implementation |
| `common/chat-diff-analyzer.cpp` | Differential analysis for auto-parser |
| `tests/test-chat-template.cpp` | Test suite |

### Summary

The llama.cpp chat template system uses a **two-tier approach**:

1. **Specialized Handlers** - For templates with known unique structures (Ministral, GPT-OSS, Functionary, Kimi, LFM2, LFM2.5, GigaChatV3)
2. **Differential Auto-Parser** - For any other Jinja template, automatically analyzes and generates a PEG parser

Key architectural insights:
- Templates are compiled once to Jinja IR and capabilities are extracted
- Handlers convert template output to structured `common_chat_params` with PEG parser + optional grammar
- Message workarounds adapt inputs to template requirements
- The auto-parser uses differential rendering to detect template structure
- All parsers use a common PEG-based infrastructure for streaming-safe output parsing

